12:["$","p",null,{"className":"pl-10","children":"The largest domain. Covers the physics of sound wave generation and propagation: wave frequency, wavelength, period, amplitude, and intensity. Also tests propagation speed through tissue, the pulse-echo principle itself (how the system calculates depth from round-trip time), spatial pulse length, duty factor, and the relationship between frequency and penetration vs. resolution. A strong grasp of this domain gives you a head start on all the others, since Doppler and image formation build on these foundations."}]
13:["$","div","02",{"className":"pt-4 border-t border-border/30","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex items-start gap-4 mb-2","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"font-mono text-xl font-bold text-teal/30 shrink-0","children":"02"}],["$","div",null,{"children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-xl font-bold text-cream","children":"Doppler Physics & Instrumentation (~22%)"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"font-mono text-xs text-cream-dim/50","children":"~24 questions"}]]}]]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"pl-10","children":"The Doppler equation, angle dependence, PW vs. CW Doppler, the Nyquist limit, aliasing and how to correct it, spectral broadening, color flow vs. power Doppler, and wall filters. RVT and RDCS candidates will recognize these as the physics underlying every waveform they produce. See our dedicated Doppler Physics guide for a full breakdown of this domain."}]]}]
14:["$","div","03",{"className":"pt-4 border-t border-border/30","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex items-start gap-4 mb-2","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"font-mono text-xl font-bold text-teal/30 shrink-0","children":"03"}],["$","div",null,{"children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-xl font-bold text-cream","children":"Transducer Mechanisms (~18%)"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"font-mono text-xs text-cream-dim/50","children":"~20 questions"}]]}]]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"pl-10","children":"Piezoelectric effect, transducer construction (matching layer, backing material, piezoelectric element), near field vs. far field (Fresnel vs. Fraunhofer zones), beam focusing (fixed vs. dynamic), transducer frequency and bandwidth, mechanical vs. electronic arrays, linear vs. curved vs. phased arrays, and the tradeoffs between them. The ARDMS tests your ability to select the appropriate transducer for a clinical scenario."}]]}]
15:["$","div","04",{"className":"pt-4 border-t border-border/30","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex items-start gap-4 mb-2","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"font-mono text-xl font-bold text-teal/30 shrink-0","children":"04"}],["$","div",null,{"children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-xl font-bold text-cream","children":"Image Formation & Optimization (~17%)"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"font-mono text-xs text-cream-dim/50","children":"~19 questions"}]]}]]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"pl-10","children":"How B-mode images are formed from pulse-echo data, frame rate, line density, depth, time-gain compensation (TGC), overall gain, dynamic range, gray-scale processing, digital scan conversion, and image persistence. Also covers real-time versus compound imaging, harmonic imaging, and spatial compound imaging. The ARDMS expects you to know which controls to adjust to optimize a suboptimal image — and why."}]]}]
16:["$","div","05",{"className":"pt-4 border-t border-border/30","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex items-start gap-4 mb-2","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"font-mono text-xl font-bold text-teal/30 shrink-0","children":"05"}],["$","div",null,{"children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-xl font-bold text-cream","children":"Artifact Recognition (~11%)"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"font-mono text-xs text-cream-dim/50","children":"~12 questions"}]]}]]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"pl-10","children":"Reverberation, ring-down, posterior acoustic shadowing, posterior acoustic enhancement, mirror image, refraction/side lobe artifacts, and grating lobes. The key ARDMS approach: you must recognize the artifact, understand its mechanism, and know whether it's clinically significant or can be misidentified as pathology. Artifact questions are often presented as clinical scenarios with images described in the question stem."}]]}]
17:["$","div","06",{"className":"pt-4 border-t border-border/30","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex items-start gap-4 mb-2","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"font-mono text-xl font-bold text-teal/30 shrink-0","children":"06"}],["$","div",null,{"children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-xl font-bold text-cream","children":"Bioeffects & Safety (~7%)"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"font-mono text-xs text-cream-dim/50","children":"~8 questions"}]]}]]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"pl-10","children":"Thermal and mechanical bioeffects, thermal index (TI) and mechanical index (MI), ALARA principle (As Low As Reasonably Achievable), and FDA output limits. The SPI also tests acoustic output parameters: ISATA (intensity spatial average temporal average) and others. This is the smallest domain but reliably produces 7–9 questions, and candidates who skip it for larger domains consistently leave points on the table."}]]}]
18:["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold text-cream pt-6","children":"How to Use This Blueprint"}]
19:["$","p",null,{"children":"Spend your study time proportionally. If you have 60 days, invest roughly 15 days on Pulse-Echo, 13 on Doppler, 11 on Transducers, 10 on Image Formation, 7 on Artifacts, and 4 on Bioeffects. SonoPrep's domain analytics track your flashcard performance by domain so you can see exactly where your gaps are and redirect your effort accordingly."}]
